<subSubSection box="[199,1171,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,824]" box="[199,1171,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the province where the 
<typeStatus box="[907,1005,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="438" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,655,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[736,875,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulpianus">
<emphasis box="[736,875,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="438">P. vulpianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it can be distinguished by the frontal callus almost snow white, usually without brown to black patches, but occasionally they appear at lateral sides, but not in lower half. The hind femur completely yellow. The middle of the genital capsule with a pair of sharply pointed structures. The aedeagal complex bipartite, its apical 
<number box="[747,757,764,788]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[769,783,764,788]" pageId="5" pageNumber="438" value="3.0">3</number>
is scissors-like, basal part considrably swollen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
